<ce:para>The effect of new technology integration on the performance of a power grid consisting of a variety of power generation plants was studied. The process was formulated as a mixed integer linear programming model and implemented in GAMS (General Algebraic Modeling System). The effect of parameter uncertainties on coal price and natural gas price was evaluated. The optimization results demonstrated how to achieve the carbon emission/mitigation goal, while minimizing costs and also determining the configuration of the OPG fleet in terms of generation mix, capacity mix, and optimal configuration. Up to 60% carbon reduction can be achieved when new technologies were integrated for every scenario. Cost of electricity decreased when new technologies were integrated in every scenario. Sensitivity analysis showed that increases in coal and natural gas prices do not change the optimal generation mix and configuration. This is an abstract of a paper presented at the AiChE Spring National Meeting &amp; 5th Global Congress on Process Safety (Tampa, FL 4/26-30/2009).</ce:para>
